Rating: 3
I read all the reviews before trying this cake and I'm glad I did. I added 1/2 cup of coconut to the batter and a tablespoon of rum and cream of coconut. I also added 1 tablespoon of rum to the cream of coconut rum glaze and poked the cake with a fork before brushing the glaze on. It turned out great. My tips: For those that are having trouble Coco Lopez brand cream of coconut head straight to your local liquor store, it is a staple for pinacoloda. Before finding it there I did found the Goya and La Cena brands at a local ethnic supermarket but unlike Coco Lopez the first ingredient was not coconut so I see why this brand is suggested. Also for those that struggled with the adjustable blade slicer don't even think about it I just used a vegetable peeler and I got the same gorgeous coconut slivers without the risk of losing valuable appendages. I also baked my coconut slivers on parchment paper to alleviate too much browning and easy removal from the baking sheet. Also for those without a Whole Foods near them try an Asian supermarket for the young coconut. In the future to add some more moisture I will add a little half and half to the batter. Some reviewers also added coconut rum and coconut extract which I think will be a welcome addition. I will also add the glaze as soon as transfer the cake from the pan.

