Rating: 3
As written it seems the cake would be disappointing but with some small adjustments I think it is worth making again. I added ¾ cup of finely grated fresh coconut to the batter and I stirred in 3T of dark rum to the ¾ c of cream of coconut that is brushed into the warm cake. That made the cream of coconut thin enough to soak into the cake; it tasted fabulous and took care of the no rum or coconut in the cake issue. : o I would plan on making and glazing the cake the day before serving to allow the glaze to harden before adding the icing. I did poke the top of the cake with a bamboo skewer to help it soak in. When making the icing I ended up not adding the heavy cream it seemed to me it would have been too thin and it was perfect without it. The cake did settle quite a bit in the center while cooling even though it was fully baked. If you turn it upside down on the plate it does help some. I dont know if baking it longer would be a help with that but I might give it a try. I made it in a long narrow loaf pan and at the last minute decided to cut up the large coconut into smaller pieces to make cutting and serving easier. Though not as dramatic it was still a nice presentation.

